An application profile “customises one or more existing specifications potentially for a given use case or a policy domain adding an end to end narrative describing and ensuring the interoperability of its underlying specification(s)”.

The narrative of how a given specification or a set of specifications is applied for a particular use case. Additional information:
  • A specification can be configured for one specific application in a given context or domain. For example, each NATO profile is a family of specifications that has been configured with a very particular application in mind.
A collection of interrelated and/or complementary specifications, standards or application profiles and the explanation of how they are combined, used or both.
Area of requirements addressed by the specification.

documentation.value: This property contains the main identifier for the scope, e.g. the URI or another unique identifier.
This property contains a free-text account of the Scope. This property can be repeated for parallel language versions of the description.

properties.documentation:
Set of agreed, descriptive and normative statements about how an specification should be designed or made. Additional information:
  • Statements may take the form of principles, requirements, recommendations and non-normative diagrams and examples, etc.
  • A specification can be related to activities (e.g. procedure document, process specification and test specification), or products (e.g. product specification, performance specification and drawing).
Source: ISO standard (ISO 9000:200518), used by EIRA
